{{Underlinked|date=December 2014}}

The Lone Star Producing Co. 1–27 '''Bertha Rogers hole''' or well was an oil-exploratory hole drilled in [[Washita County, Oklahoma]] in 1974, and was the world's deepest hole until it was surpassed in 1979 by the [[Kola Superdeep Borehole]], dug by the USSR.

It took [[Lone Star Producing Co.|Lone Star]] a little over a year and a half to reach 31,441 feet (9,583 m), a depth of almost six miles. During drilling, the well encountered enormous pressure – almost 25,000 psi (172,369 kPa). No commercial hydrocarbons were found before drilling hit a molten sulfur deposit, which melted the drill bit. The well was plugged back and completed in the Granite Wash from 11,000 to 13,200 feet as a natural gas producer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oklahoma Corporation Commission completion report (form 1002A) dated September 3, 1974 |url=http://imaging.occeweb.com/OG/Well%20Records/00000005/OCC_OG_0G5BFM7_1L8M2C4.pdf |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307092759/http://imaging.occeweb.com/OG/Well%20Records/00000005/OCC_OG_0G5BFM7_1L8M2C4.pdf |format=pdf |archivedate=March 7, 2016 |accessdate=December 1, 2018}}</ref>

