The '''Frank R. Bowerman Landfill''' is a [[landfill]] in the western [[Santa Ana Mountains]], in [[Orange County, California]]. It opened in 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calrecycle.ca.gov/LEA/hearing/Notice/OCNotice.pdf |title=public notice on proposed revision of the Bowerman Landfill permit |format=PDF |accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> The landfill is located between [[Limestone Canyon Regional Park]] and [[California State Route 241|State Route 241]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocweekly.com/locations/frank-r-bowerman-landfill-635061/ |title=OC Weekly website |publisher=Ocweekly.com |accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref>

It is one of the largest landfills in California and the ninth largest in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wheeler|first=Ian|title=From Buried Trash, A Treasure Chest of Energy|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=October 27, 2013|page=News 35}}</ref> It contains an estimated 31 million tons of waste.

==History==
It was named after Professor [[Frank R. Bowerman]], former director of environmental engineering programs, at the [[University of Southern California]], and former president of the [[American Academy of Environmental Engineers]] and the American Academy for Environmental Protection. Bowerman was also a technical consultant to the environmentally themed science fiction film ''[[Soylent Green]]''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gEfuG590qNoC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=%22American+Academy+of+Environmental+Engineers%22+frank+bowerman&source=bl&ots=W-EX3WTipP&sig=0x_0XNb8Io97qFqmzCYg3o083R4&hl=en&ei=wN9eTM2rOY3WtQO5zOWRDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CCQQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=%22American%20Academy%20of%20Environmental%20Engineers%22%20frank%20bowerman&f=false |title=American alchemy: the history of solid waste management in the United States – H. Lanier Hickman – Google Books |publisher=Google Books |accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=atomjack |url=http://fusionanomaly.net/soylentgreen.html |title=fUSION Anomaly. Soylent Green |publisher=Fusionanomaly.net |accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref>

==Landfill gas utilization==
It is the site for the world’s first commercial [[Landfill gas utilization|landfill gas to liquid natural gas]] project, the Bowerman Landfill Project, constructed by [[Prometheus Energy]], an [[LNG]] fuel company based in [[Redmond, Washington]], and [[Montauk Energy]], a capital investment firm.<ref>[http://www.prometheus-energy.com/whatwedo/bowerman.php Prometheus Energy website]</ref><ref>[http://www.montaukenergycapital.com/bowerman.asp Montauk Energy website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303051732/http://www.montaukenergycapital.com/bowerman.asp |date=March 3, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sultan, Michael|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-33331080_ITM |title="Prometheus Energy Announces First Delivery of LNG by LNG-Fuelled Vehicle", Business Wire, October 31, 2007 (summary) |publisher=Accessmylibrary.com |accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waste-management-world.com/index/display/article-display/296001/articles/waste-management-world/volume-8/issue-3/features/fuelling-new-ideas.html |title="Fuelling new ideas: Conversion of biogas into LNG becomes reality", Dan Clarkson, Waste Management World website |publisher=Waste-management-world.com |accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref>

