{{see also|Tropical agriculture}} [[image:Tapped rubber tree.jpg|thumb|185px|[[Latex]] being collected from an incised [[Hevea brasiliensis|rubber tree]] (''Hevea brasiliensis''), and a bucket of collected latex]]
'''Tropical horticulture''' is a branch of [[horticulture]] that studies and cultivates plants in the [[tropics]], i.e., the [[Equatorial climate|equatorial]] regions of the world. The field is sometimes known by the [[portmanteau]] "TropHort".
Tropical horticulture includes plants such as perennial woody plants ([[arboriculture]]), ornamentals ([[floriculture]]), vegetables ([[olericulture]]), and fruits ([[pomology]]) including grapes ([[viticulture]]). The origin of many of these crops is not in the tropics but in temperate zones. Their adoption to tropical climatic conditions is an objective of [[breeding in the wild|breeding]]. Many important crops, however, are indigenous to the tropics. The latter embrace perennial crops such as [[Elaeis guineensis|oil palm]], vegetables including [[okra]], field crops such as [[rice]] and [[sugarcane]], and particularly fruits including [[pineapple]], [[banana]], [[papaya]], and [[mango]].
Since the tropics represent 36 percent of the earth's surface and 20 percent of its land surface, the potential of tropical horticulture is huge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/tropical/ |title=''Tropical Horticulture'' |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427054655/http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/tropical/ |archivedate=April 27, 2009 }}</ref> In contrast to [[Temperate climate|temperate]] regions, [[Natural environment|environmental]] conditions in the tropics are defined less by seasonal temperature fluctuations and more by seasonality of precipitation. Thus the [[climate]] in the greater part of the tropics is characterized by distinct wet and dry seasons, although such variation is reduced in locations closer to the equator (±5° latitude). Temperature conditions in the tropics are affected by elevation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajol.info/index.php/ijotafs |title=''Tropical Agriculture and Food Systems'' |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090623234040/http://ajol.info/index.php/ijotafs |archivedate=June 23, 2009 }}</ref> in which contrasting warmer and colder climate areas in the tropics can be differentiated,<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nEbQAtyUJt8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=tropical+plants&hl=en&sa=X&ei=47KCT4aDMcTYiAKrpMmbAw&ved=0CGAQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=tropical%20plants&f=false | title=Physiological Ecology of Tropical Plants | publisher=Springer | year=1997 |accessdate=April 9, 2012 | author=Lüttge, Ulrich}} {{ISBN|3540611614}}</ref>{{RP|4-5}} and highland areas in the tropics can consequently be more favourable for production of temperate plant species than are lowland areas.
==Types of plants== {{see also|Tropical agriculture#Common tropical horticulture crops}} {{see also|List of fruits#Tropical fruits}}
Both [[Vascular plant|vascular]] and [[Non-vascular plant|non-vascular]] plants grow in tropical environments. Plants indigenous to the tropics are usually cold sensitive and adapted to receiving high levels of [[Sunlight|solar radiation]]. They are sensitive to small variations in photoperiod ("short day" plants), and can be adapted to extended drought, high precipitation and/or distinct wet and dry seasons. High night temperatures are a major hindrance to adopting temperate crops (e.g., [[tomato]]es) to the tropical lowlands. Furthermore, such conditions promote high [[Cellular respiration|respiration]] rates of plants, resulting in comparably lower net [[photosynthesis]] rates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akademisains.gov.my/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=202&Itemid=9 |title=''Tropical Horticulture and Gardening'' |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308151218/http://www.akademisains.gov.my/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=202&Itemid=9 |archivedate=March 8, 2009 }}</ref>
